The Beck family, three generations strong, set out to harvest disease-free oysters after years of waiting.
Oystermen agreed to wait until the oysters reached legal size, leading to a decline in the number of people oystering in Maryland.
Concerns over introducing Asian oysters into the Chesapeake Bay have sparked debate among officials and researchers.
Cleanup efforts have been slow, with challenges in securing workers for seafood processing plants.
The decline of the native oyster population and pollution issues continue to plague the bay, prompting calls for more research and funding for restoration efforts.
